As a staffer to Harry Reid, I witnessed up close the transactional nature o=
f political
power=E2=80=94an education that I poured into my second career as a journal=
ist. Now, as chief Washington correspondent for Puck, I=E2=80=99m delving d=
eeper than ever into the (mostly) smokeless back rooms of the Hill, where t=
he second Trump era will come alive.=C2=A0

Leigh Ann Caldwell ( https://puck.news/author/leigh-ann-caldwell/?utm_campa=
ign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F25%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F25%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Leigh Ann Caldwell ( https://puck.news/author/leigh-ann-caldwell/?utm_campa=
ign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F25%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F25%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

When I was finishing up college at North Carolina State, I found myself at =
a crossroads
that I thought would determine the rest of my life: I could either move to =
rural North Carolina and work as a journalist at a local radio station, or =
shelve those plans and instead go to work for one of the most powerful peop=
le in Washington. Worried that I might never be promoted to reporter, I put=
 journalism aside, and joined the staff of Senator Harry Reid, the former b=
oxer turned power broker who represented my home state of Nevada. It was, a=
s it turns out, a fateful decision that ultimately led me to Puck, where I=
=E2=80=99ll be covering Capitol Hill.

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99d never been to Washington. When I arrived, the atmosphere was ex=
traordinarily charged, perceptible even to a 21-year-old political novice. =
The Supreme Court had just handed George W. Bush the election and the Senat=
e was split 50-50. From my perch as assistant to Susan McCue, Reid=E2=80=99=
s glass-ceiling-shattering chief of staff, I acted as a gatekeeper to the g=
atekeeper and witnessed first-hand how power,
soft and hard, was wielded.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Reid was a transactional dealmaker, a real creature of the chamber, obsesse=
d with his own power and whatever benefited Nevada. At the time, he=E2=80=
=99d somehow persuaded Senator Jim Jeffords, a moderate Republican disgrunt=
led with his party=E2=80=99s conservative turn, to drop his party affiliati=
on and vote with the Democrats, a masterstroke that gave Democrats the majo=
rity
and the ability to slow Bush=E2=80=99s agenda, quickly putting Reid on the =
path to becoming leader.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It was, in many ways, the perfect training ground for a political reporter.=
 Riding shotgun with McCue, I observed the inside machinations of Reid=E2=
=80=99s yearlong, round-the-clock strategy sessions to persuade, arm-twist,=
 and barter with enough senators to kill the Yucca Mountain nuclear waste r=
epository in Nevada=E2=80=94a NIMBYist move
that pitted most of the country against my home state.

=C2=A0

My extremely low-paying but eye-opening job left me uninterested in partici=
pating in partisan battles, but it also armed me with a new understanding o=
f how the most powerful people operate. It was an awareness that would keep=
 pulling me back to Capitol Hill. After I left Reid=E2=80=99s office, I mov=
ed to New York to pursue the career I actually wanted:
journalism. I interned and freelanced, but mostly waited tables. Eventually=
, I became a radio reporter during Bush=E2=80=99s lame duck years and the b=
eginning of Barack Obama=E2=80=99s term, when the economy was crashing and =
the wealthy got rewarded=E2=80=94seeds of the populist backlash that led to=
 Donald Trump.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

During the 2016 presidential campaign, at NBC News, I covered Republican
donors and grassroots organizers. Power and influence had been flipped on i=
ts head: Wealthy G.O.P. fundraisers who had driven the party=E2=80=99s agen=
da and played huge roles in determining its presidential nominee were late =
to the game. It was the populist base that fell in line behind Trump and dr=
ove his success=E2=80=94the same base that he continues to use and manipula=
te to his everlasting advantage.

=C2=A0

Eventually,
my beat pivoted to the impact of Trump=E2=80=99s first term on the Hill. (I=
 still recall fondly the afternoon when a happy-go-lucky John McCain, just =
back from brain cancer treatment, joined a FaceTime call with my kids=E2=80=
=94hours before he provided the decisive vote against Obamacare repeal.) Tr=
ump hadn=E2=80=99t yet figured out how to mold Washington=E2=80=94the town=
=E2=80=99s rhythms and rituals were largely alien to him=E2=80=94but his st=
aff, and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, knew how to mold
the Supreme Court. I covered the sexual assault allegations against Brett K=
avanaugh, his controversial confirmation hearings, and Republican efforts t=
o ensure he was confirmed. It was an extension of the #MeToo movement, wher=
e the power balance seemed to be shifting, even temporarily, away from trad=
itional centers of influence. My reporting from that era helped to reveal t=
hat the Hill=E2=80=99s version of an ethics office had shielded the accused=
 from allegations and
repercussions.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The Trump years were a time of remarkable and initially surprising growth f=
or the media. I joined the best political reporters in the country at The W=
ashington Post, one of the most financially stable news organizations backe=
d by one of the richest men in the world. A winning combination, I thought.=
 I helmed the Post=E2=80=99s flagship morning political newsletter during a
tumultuous time in Congress, breaking news about efforts to oust then Speak=
er Kevin McCarthy and the nearly monthlong journey to find his replacement.=
 I wrote the definitive final act of the years-long power struggle between =
McConnell and Reid, my old boss.

=C2=A0

My years at the Post brought me deep into the inner sanctum of power. I det=
ailed why the earnest new speaker of the
House, Mike Johnson, was willing to lose his job to fund Ukraine=E2=80=99s =
defense against Russia. (Months later, during an interview with Johnson, he=
 asked me whether I was the person who=E2=80=99d asked him at a news confer=
ence why he=E2=80=99d put everything on the line for Ukraine. He told me it=
 was a tough question but one he appreciated and was pleased to be able to =
articulate.) I broke stories about the Democrats=E2=80=99 pressure campaign=
 during the torturous three weeks after President
Biden=E2=80=99s disastrous debate performance and his agonizing decision to=
 drop out.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As an anchor for Washington Post Live, I chatted with Senate Democratic lea=
der Chuck Schumer about artificial intelligence, pressed Senate Republican =
leader John Thune about his relationship with Trump, and held court with Ky=
rsten Sinema, who rarely talks to the
media, for 30 minutes onstage. I hosted a show that featured Republican and=
 Democratic lawmakers, in concert with one another=E2=80=94an anomaly in th=
ese polarizing times, when so many politicians fear that a picture of bipar=
tisanship will be weaponized against them.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

These days, much of journalism is in crisis, struggling to find an audience=
 and business model to stay solvent. I loved my job, but
Puck offered something new=E2=80=94the chance to have a say in how the busi=
ness of media is run, plus the ability to report aggressively and write wit=
h abandon. Puck has a vision and a voice, and I wanted to help build its in=
fluence in Washington, D.C., in general, and on the Hill, in particular.

=C2=A0

At Puck, I=E2=80=99ll return to Capitol Hill, where I=E2=80=99ll make sense=
 of the perpetual jockeying over agendas and
status. I=E2=80=99ll be writing for Puck=E2=80=99s flagship political newsl=
etter, The Best & The Brightest, starting with a regular Sunday column that=
 captures the week=E2=80=99s inside conversations on the Hill and also pres=
ages the challenges and opportunities ahead.

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99ll also take you inside the (mostly smokeless) back rooms of the =
Hill to provide a deeper understanding of how power is used and sometimes a=
bused. I=E2=80=99ll introduce
you to characters you didn=E2=80=99t know you needed to know. I=E2=80=99ll =
reveal the cliques, the moods, and the infighting that makes this place uni=
que. When Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene suddenly shifts her tone toward Johns=
on, I=E2=80=99ll tell you why. It=E2=80=99s the details and the color and t=
he conversations that most fascinate me in an institution where process is =
actually not the story.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99ll be a blast. Plus, isn=E2=80=99t Puck
everyone=E2=80=99s favorite Shakespeare character?

=E2=80=8A

See you soon,

Leigh Ann

